&lt;h3&gt;Yom Ha&#039;atzma&#039;ut&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;General Notes&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yom Ha&#039;atzma&#039;ut is a celebration of Israel&#039;s Independence. There are several potential liturgies for this day; many include Hallel and some include a Torah reading. Mishkan T&#039;fila includes a service for Yom Ha&#039;atzma&#039;ut on page 538, and the Plaut Torah commentary suggests Torah and Haftarah readings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Torah Reading&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Deuteronomy 8:1-18 (P 1387, RP 1229, WTC 1094)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;or&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;11:8-21 (P 1407, RP 1238, WTC 1104)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;or&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;26:1-11 (P 1508, RP 1350, WTC 1193)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;or&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;30:1-16 (P 1540, RP 1375, WTC 1224)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Haftarah&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Isaiah 60:1-22 (P 1669, RP 1474)&lt;/p&gt;
